-- Proof by Exhaustion (Finite Case Analysis)
--
-- STATUS: CONCEPTUAL (Issue #156)
-- This file EXPLAINS how finite exhaustion affects credence (product or min
-- aggregation). The checker does NOT verify these aggregation rules; this is
-- documentation of the DESIGN. No actual finite case combinator is implemented.
--
-- Classical: Check all cases, conclude universal
-- CredTT: Stable if each case stable AND aggregation stable
--
-- Example: Prove 4-color theorem by checking all configurations
-- Classical: Check all 1936 cases, done
-- CredTT: Each case @ c_i, result @ product or minimum

-- Finite exhaustion with n cases:
-- Case 1 @ c1, Case 2 @ c2, ..., Case n @ cn
-- Universal @ aggregation(c1, c2, ..., cn)

-- With stable cases (all at credence 1):
postulate case1 : P_for_red @ 1
postulate case2 : P_for_green @ 1
postulate case3 : P_for_blue @ 1
postulate case4 : P_for_yellow @ 1

-- Aggregation: AND of all cases
-- 1 * 1 * 1 * 1 = 1
-- Result is stable

stable case1
stable case2
stable case3
stable case4

-- With one weak case:
postulate weak_case : P_for_purple @ 1/2

-- Now: 1 * 1 * 1 * 0.5 = 0.5
-- Result degrades to weakest link (actually worse: product)

-- This is why computer-checked proofs matter:
-- 1936 cases, each at 0.9999 credence
-- Product: 0.9999^1936 = 0.824 (NOT near 1!)

-- Classical logic: all cases check -> universal true
-- CredTT: all cases check @ c -> universal @ f(c, n)

-- The function f depends on aggregation method:
-- Product: c^n (degrades exponentially)
-- Minimum: min(c_i) (degrades to worst case)
-- Average: mean(c_i) (doesn't capture dependencies)

-- Computer-verified proofs:
-- If each step verified with certainty (c=1), product = 1
-- If each step has epsilon error, product degrades

-- This explains why formal verification is valuable:
-- It achieves c=1 for each step
-- Informal proofs might have c=0.99 per step
-- Over many steps, this accumulates significant uncertainty

-- Stability: Stable1 only if ALL cases Stable1
